  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good psychological thriller movies of 2015?",
  "response": "2015 was a strong year for psychological thrillers, offering a variety of films that delve deep into the complexities of the human mind, suspense, and intricate narratives. Here are some of the standout psychological thriller movies from that year:\n\n1. **Gone Girl**\n   - **Director:** David Fincher\n   - **Synopsis:** Based on Gillian Flynn's bestselling novel, this film follows the mysterious disappearance of Amy Dunne (Rosamund Pike) and the ensuing media frenzy that puts her husband, Nick (Ben Affleck), under intense suspicion. The movie masterfully explores themes of deception, media manipulation, and the dark facets of marriage.\n   - **Why Watch:** David Fincher\u2019s meticulous direction combined with stellar performances makes this a gripping and twist-filled experience.\n\n2. **The Gift**\n   - **Director:** Joel Edgerton\n   - **Synopsis:** This film centers on a married couple, Simon (Jason Bateman) and Robyn (Rebecca Hall), whose lives are disrupted by the unexpected arrival of Gordo (Joel Edgerton), an acquaintance from Simon's past. What begins as seemingly thoughtful gifts soon turns into a series of psychological games and unsettling revelations.\n   - **Why Watch:** Joel Edgerton not only directs but also delivers a compelling performance, adding layers of suspense and mystery.\n\n3. **Enemy**\n   - **Director:** Denis Villeneuve\n   - **Synopsis:** Starring Jake Gyllenhaal in a dual role, \"Enemy\" tells the story of a man who discovers his exact look-alike after watching a movie. This revelation leads him into a perplexing and surreal journey, blurring the lines between reality and illusion.\n   - **Why Watch:** The film's dreamlike narrative and thought-provoking symbolism make it a standout in the psychological thriller genre.\n\n4. **The Invitation**\n   - **Director:** Karyn Kusama\n   - **Synopsis:** During a dinner party hosted by his ex-wife and her new husband, Will (Logan Marshall-Green) becomes increasingly suspicious that something sinister is unfolding. As tensions rise, the evening takes a dark and unexpected turn.\n   - **Why Watch:** \"The Invitation\" excels in building tension and delivering a slow-burn thriller experience that keeps viewers on edge until the very end.\n\n5. **Stutterer**\n   - **Director:** Benjamin Cleary\n   - **Synopsis:** This short film, which won the Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film, follows a man named Greenwood (Matthew Needham) who struggles with a severe stutter. As he prepares to meet his online girlfriend in person for the first time, the film delves into his internal anxieties and fears.\n   - **Why Watch:** Though brief, \"Stutterer\" offers a poignant and intimate look into the psychological challenges of communication and vulnerability.\n\n6. **The Stanford Prison Experiment**\n   - **Director:** Kyle Patrick Alvarez\n   - **Synopsis:** Based on the true events of the 1971 psychological study, the film portrays the intense and often disturbing dynamics that emerge when students are assigned roles as guards and prisoners in a mock prison environment.\n   - **Why Watch:** The movie provides a chilling exploration of power, authority, and human behavior under extreme conditions.\n\nThese films offer a range of psychological thrills, from intricate plot twists and character studies to intense suspense and moral quandaries. Whether you're looking for a deep narrative, exceptional performances, or mind-bending scenarios, 2015 has a psychological thriller that can captivate and intrigue you.",
